<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-661-055  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 661 055.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Vision Graphics andamp; Image Processing  Dec 1990 v52 n3p341(19).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Simultaneous fitting of several planes to point sets using neuralnetworks. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kamgar-Parsi, Behrooz; Kamgar-Parsi, Behzad.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A method is developed for fitting a number of lines or planes tosets of points in three-dimensional space that uses an artificialneural network to achieve a 'very good' though maybe not optimalsolution.andP;  The extrapolation of line, surface, and shape from setsof points is a central problem in pattern recognition and computervision.andP;  The problem becomes exponentially more complex with theincreasing number of points.andP;  The new approach uses anoptimization technique similar to the K-means method of clusteringdata points into compact clubs but is more robust when resolvingnoisy data and can be generalized to fitting any planes to pointsets.andP;  A modified analog neural network is determined to be bestsuited to the optimization problem.andP;  Simulation comparison of theneural network method with the Phillips-Rosenfeld algorithmdemonstrates the superiority of the new approach.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Neural NetworksObject RecognitionTwo-Dimensional GraphicsPattern RecognitionModelingOptimizationThree-Dimensional GraphicsNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablegraph.andO;Caption:   Representation of a possible solution for fitting 3 lines to 10points. (table)Comparison of the Phillips-Rosenfeld algorithm and the Neural Netalgorithm. (table)Best fit of two lines to sets of points without and affected bynoise. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>